column168: On 09/05/2019 at 1022 hours (Eastern Time) it was reported at Montgomery Yard (CSXT), located in Montgomery, AL, that tank car CSXT993327, a loaded tank car of fuel oil, released product from the area of the manway.  Marion Environmental (CSX Hazmat Contractor) was dispatched to the scene.  Marion Environmental arrived onsite and confirmed product released from the manway onto the sides of the car.  Marion Environmental discovered that the manway nozzle gasket had deteriorated and was the cause of the release. The shipper, Transflo (Ryan Prewitt 606-344-5531) was notified.  Note: The shipper listed on the waybill is showing as CSXT General Yardmaster but the car was loaded by Transflo.  Also the total estimated capacity on the car listed in the report is an estimate as the exact amount was not recorded at the time of the incident.  Marion Environmental replaced the gasket and secured the car.    NAR Code: 209 (5 pts) Manway gasket deteriorated  5(5+1+0) x (2+0) = 60 NARRI     Montgomery, AL – 09/04/19 – CSXT993327 – Fuel Oil Combustible Liquid

column168: Driver was in transit from Texas to Tennessee for  first unload of two part delivery.  When he awoke and performed his pre-trip on the morning of the spill incident all was good with product, truck, and trailer.  As he traveled toward his destination the road was bumpy and the temperature was hot.  The mixture was agitated by the travel and the heat and caused the TPs to swell.  driver noticed liquid exiting rear of his box trailer and pulled over in safe place to investigate.  Noticed the spill and called his company right away.  Company instructed driver regarding containing the spill and insuring he maintained a watchful vigil while Clean-up crew was dispatched and CHEMTREC and Arkansas EMS were notified.  report #s 2019091000174  and 30566 respectively. It was determined that the swelling of the TP caused the bottom seam, near the metal tag, to split and allow the liquid to escape.
column169: The product that was shipped was a mixture and  one of the mixtures was Hydrogen Peroxide - which reacts to heat and agitation.  The totes were purposely left less than 1/2 full to compensate for building of pressure.  Either the product is going to have to be shipped during times of cooler temperatures, or possible in a trailer that can keep the product cooled in order to reduce the possibility of swelling.  Might could use a seamless container the ship the product that would be more resistant to damage when the product gases expand.

A UNIVAR SOLUTIONS DRIVER WAS PUMPING OFF BULK ACETONE FROM A TANKER AT A CUSTOMER (AMERICAN JETWAY) FACILITY. CUSTOMER WAS TOTING OFF THE MATERIAL FROM THE TRUCK THROUGH A TRANSFER LINE IN THEIR FILLING ROOM WHERE THE DRIVER CANNOT SEE THE TOTES. THE FILLING OF THE TOTES IS CONTROLLED BY THE CUSTOMER. THE CUSTOMER LEFT THE BOTTOM VALVE ON ONE OF THEIR TOTES OPEN AND MATERIAL THAT WAS PUMPING INTO THE TOP O THE TOTE CAME THROUGH THE BOTTOM VALVE AND ONTO THEIR FLOOR. DRIVER ESTIMATES THAT APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF MATERIAL WAS RELEASED BEFORE THE CUSTOMER NOTICED AND TOLD THE DRIVER TO SHUT DOWN PUMPING OPERATIONS. THE SPILL DURATION WAS LESS THAN 5 MINUTES. THE CAUSE OF THE SPILL WAS HUMAN ERROR AND HE CUSTOMER ADMITTED RESPONSIBILITY FOR THE SPILL AND CLEANED UP THE MATERIAL INTERNALLY. ALL MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED INSIDE THE CUSTOMER'S FACILITY ON A CONCRETE FLOOR. NO LIQUID MATERIAL WAS RELEASED TO THE ENVIRONMENT NOR WAS THE SPILL AMOUNT WAS ABOVE THE REPORTABLE QUANTITY (RQ) SO THE SPILL WAS NOT REPORTED TO ANY REGULATORY AGENCY.
column169: THE OSS TEAM WILL DOUBLE CHECK ALL VALVE CAPS AFTER THE DRIVER SECURES IT.

column168: The truck was initially loaded at the shipper's location and included a mixed shipment of 2 cubic yard  boxes and drums.  The boxes were loaded into the truck first using a pallet jack.  The pallet jack was  left under the second box and the subsequent 55 gallon waste drums were loaded around the two  boxes.  All containers were secured in place with a cargo strap.  While backing up to the Veolia  loading dock in Fremont, CA, the load apparently shifted and one of the 55 gallon drums bumped  the corner of the pallet jack, causing a puncture.  The leak was noticed as it began dripping from  under the bed of truck cargo area.  A berm of absorbent was placed to contain the spill on the  concrete pad.  The truck was offloaded and the leaking drum was overpacked into an 85 gallon  drum within approximately 15 minutes of the leak observation.  The major portion of the leak was  contained on the truck with approximately 5 gallons that leaked onto the concrete dock area.  The  spilled material was cleaned up on the tuck and in the concrete area by Veolia.  The City of Fremont Fire Dept/CUPA was notified at 4:40 pm to the non-emergency dispatcher, badge #784.  No  response was required.
column169: The Veolia Fremont field technicians will be trained on cargo loading and will include a hands-on  training where drivers/technicians will be presented with various scenarios of loading complications. This training will also include a section on planning before routing to include specific truck capacity.

column62: Broken Component or Device; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: An odor was reported to be coming from coming from UTLX 202632. A vapor release was found at the Magnetic Gauging Device, the Magnetic Gauging Device has an internal leak, the vapor leak was stopped by securing the cap with Teflon tape. The Pressure Relief Device flange had a vapor leak, the leak was stopped by tightening all 8 bolts. The Vacuum Relief Valve had a vapor leak, the leak was stopped by replacing it with a plug. The Air Valve packing had a vapor leak, the packing was over-compressed, the bolt torque was reduced which stopped the leak. The Liquid Valve packing had a vapor leak, the packing was insufficient, 1 piece of 1/4 Teflon cord was added which stopped the leak. The car was checked with Snoop (Leak Detector) and an air monitor over a 4 hour period on 9/13, no release was found, the car is secure and no longer leaking.

RONALD MEYER (FARMER) WAS TRANSPORTING THE NURSE TANK TO THE SCALE HOUSE TO WEIGH AND PROCEED TO HIS FARM. WHEN TURNING OFF OF 247TH ONTO 2ND STREET THE NURSE TANK ROLLED ONTO ITS SIDE. BREAKING THE ROLL CAGE AND DAMAGING BOTH THE LIQUID FILL VALVE AND THE VAPOR RETURN VALVE. THE VAPOR RETURN VALVE WAS DAMAGED ENOUGH TO CAUSE A SMALL LEAK (DRIP). THE LOCAL FIRE AND POLICE DEPARTMENTS WERE CALLED AT APPROXIMATELY 4:08 PM AND ARRIVED ON SCENE SHORTLY THERE AFTER. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT APPLIED WATER ONTO RELEASE KNOCKING DOWN PLUME, AND APPLYING SHOP RAGS ON VALVE. CAUSING A FREEZE DRY AFFECT, STOPPING THE RELEASE. ONCE RELEASE WAS STOPPED A VARIABLE REACH FORKLIFT WAS USED TO TURN THE NURSE TANK BANK ONTO ITS WHEELS. THE TANK WAS THEN TRANSPORTED BACK TO THE STORAGE AREA WHERE THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TANK.
column169: I SUGGEST OUR SALES TEAM TAKE THE TIME TO REMIND OUR FARMERS THE HAZARDS OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA AND HOW TAKING CORNERS AT A HIGH RATED OF SPEED CAN CAUSE ROLL OVERS DUE TO THE SURGING OF FLUID INSIDE THE TANK.

column168: On September 13, 2019, at 2017 EST, ERTS was notified by XPO Logistics Terminal XWK of a release of UN3266 Corrosive Liquid. Terminal personnel stated that due to improper loading a 330 gallon poly tote was punctured by a forklift. Terminal personnel requested a contractor to clean the release.  At 0330 EST on September 14, 2019, contractors arrived on site and confirmed approximately 150 gallons of product released to the trailer floor and asphalt below. Approximately 100 gallons of the product released outside of the trailer, onto the parking lot. Size of areas impacted were approximately 2' x 100 yards in the parking lot and 12' x 25 yards on the parking lot right outside of the trailer. A 20' x 8' area inside the trailer was impacted. Due to the product becoming flammable once dry, contractors pressure washed the release and collected it with a vacuum truck. The impacted pallets and trailer floor were cut up and containerized with water to keep the product from drying up. Contractors generated a total of (13) 55 gallon poly drums, (3) 85 gallon poly drums, and (2) 330 gallon poly totes of cleanup debris. A roll off of the trailer floor was also generated. All waste is currently staged on site for XPO to manage.

Yulee, FL – 9/11/2019 – TILX 401333 – ACRYLONITRILE, STABILIZED     On 9/11/2019 at 1346, FRA hazardous materials inspector discovered TILX 401333 with a release at  the liquid valve plug while car was at CSX / First Cost Railroad interchange in Yulee, FL.  TILX 401333,  a loaded tank car of Acrylonitrile, stabilized, was confirmed to be leaking from the liquid valve.  The car  was isolated and the First Coast Railroad made a NRC notification (report number 1257921) as well as  local fire department notification.  CSX notified CHEMTREC (report number 2019-0911-00292) and was  provided shipper contact information for Ineos USA LLC, who was notified of the incident.  HEPACO,  a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the car leaking  from the liquid valve.  The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the  shipper (Art Hurtado, phone number 630-857-7085).  Contractor personnel cleaned up the liquid  and applied new thread tape to the secondary closure plug, this stopped the release.  The shipper  then hired SPSI to replace the liquid valve and bubble leak test the car.

column63: THE TRAILER WAS A DOT 407- THE ITEMS THA
column168: Langer Transport delivered a load of gas additive to Cenex Terminal in Rensselaer, New York. The product was in a tank truck and was going to be off loaded using the pump on the tractor and hoses that the driver bought with him. When the driver arrived at Cen6x to off load he inspected his hoses and gaskets and didn't notice any issues with them so he hooked them up to the pump on the tractor and starting pumping off the load. About 45 minutes into the unloading process one of the hoses developed a crack and product sprayed and poured out of the hose and onto the ground. As soon as the driver noticed this he immediately shut everything down. He then took spill pads out of his tractor and put them over the affected area where the product hit the ground. None of the product was released into any waterways and no one was injured. It is estimated that approximately 20 gallons of product leaked out of the hose. A 3rd party cleanup crew( Mac Son) was called in to clean up the spill. They used speedy dry and Vac trucks to absorb everything and then washed the area down with a vacuum truck. The defective hose was looked at when it arrived
column169: When the driver returned to the yard we had our Maintenance Department inspect the hose that failed. We didn't notice anything out of the ordinary with the hose when we inspected it. What we believe happened here was that the hose had a small cut or gouge in it that the driver didn't see which caused it to fail when it was under pressure. Please note that Langer Transport has a procedure in place where we inspect our drivers discharge hoses on a quarterly basis. We will continue to do this procedure throughout our fleet. In this instance the drivers hoses were last inspected on August 2nd and no issues with the hoses were notated.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: On September 27, 2019, at 0248 EST, XPO Logistics terminal XDP notified ERTS of a release of an unknown product to the trailer floor. The caller reported that due to lack of blocking and bracing by the shipper, the container arrived punctured causing the release. Due to the strong odor reported by terminal and unknown trade name, ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup activities. At 0400 EST, contractors arrived on site and confirmed approximately 4 gallons of UN1791 Hypochlorite Solution "Chlor™ 125" released from a 15 gallon poly drum that was punctured by a nail from the pallet. The release impacted an area of 2' X 2' of the trailer floor, 4' X 5' of the dock floor, and 4' X 1' area below the trailer. Contractors utilized absorbents to clean the released product. The damaged drum, spent absorbents, and all other cleanup debris were containerized into a 55 gallon poly drum. The waste was left on site for terminal personnel to manage.

UPON ARRIVAL TO THE SCENE OF THE SPILL, THE DESIGNATED RESPONDER NOTICED THAT THE TWO BOTTLES WERE OUT OF THE PACKAGE WITH BOTH LIDS MISSING. THE RMP WHO DISCOVERED THE PACKAGED NOTICED THE SAME THING. AFTER INSPECTION OF THE PACKAGE IT APPEARED THAT THE REINFORCED TAPE HAD FAILED LEADING THE GLASS BOTTLES TO SLIDE OUT OF THE BOTTOM AND CRACKED THEIR LIDS OPEN.

column168: I ARRIVED IN THE DMP TO FIND A LEAKING HAZMAT PACKAGE ON THE TABLE. I DONNED MY PPE, (GOGGLES, GLOVES, BOOTS AND APRON) AND PREPARED TO RESPOND TO THE SPILL. FOLLOWING THE RELEVANT RESPONSE SHEET (CORROSIVE/OXIDIZER), I DONNED THE REQUIRED SUPPLEMENTAL PPE (SILVER SHIELD GLOVE LINERS) AND CONTINUED TO PROCESS THE SPILL. DURING THE COURSE OF THE SOLIDIFICATION/NEUTRALIZATION PROCESS, THE PRODUCT BEGAN REACTING VIOLENTLY WITH THE CLAY BASED ABSORBENT. I NOTIFIED MY CHAIN OF COMMAND, AND AN OUTSIDE RESPONDER WAS CALLED. THE PRODUCT AND ALL ASSOCIATED WAS REMOVED FROM THE PROPERTY BY THE OUTSIDE RESPONDER.

NOTIFIED (PT PRELOAD SUPERVISOR) OF A LEAKING PACKAGE. I WAS THEN NOTIFIED THAT I WAS NEEDED ON RED BELT TO RESPOND TO A LEAKER. I PUT ON MY PPE (DISPOSABLE GLOVES, SILVER SHIELD LINERS, CHEMICAL RESISTANT GLOVES, GOGGLES, APRON, AND SLEEVES) AND GRABBED MY DECISION TREE. I WENT TO THE LEAKING PACKAGE, FOLLOWED MY DECISION TREE. THE PACKAGE DID HAVE VISIBLE FUMES AND THE ODOR WAS IRRITATING WHICH WAS MAKING ME COUGH SO I ANSWERED YES TO THE FIRST BOX WHICH TOOK ME TO DO NOT ATTEMPT TO CLEAN UP AND REFER TO CONTAINMENT SHEET, ACTIVATE CHAIN OF COMMAND AN NOTIFY PE. THEN MY RMPS TOOK OVER AND THEY ACTIVATED THE CHAIN OF COMMAND.

column168: On September 26, 2019, at 0957 EST, XPO Logistics Terminal XLA notified ERTS of a release of UN2796 from a 275 gallon poly tote due to an unknown reason. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup and over packing operations. At 1250 EST, contractors arrived on site and confirmed the bung cap was not properly tightened on the tote and pooped off. As a result, the material in the tote sloshed out to a 4' x 8' area of the trailer floor. Contractors neutralized the area with sodium bicarbonate and water. The tote was wiped down, and the bung cap was tightened and secured for transit. The impacted absorbents and cleanup debris were then containerized into a 55 gallon poly drum. All waste was left on site for terminal personnel to manage.

column62: Corrosion - Interior; Human Error; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: FERGUSON ACKNOWLEDGES AN INCIDENT ON SEPTEMBER 9, 2019 INVOLVING A ONE PIECE SHIPMENT TRANSPORTED BY THE UNITED PARCEL SERVICE UNDER WAYBILL NUMBER 1ZV9Y9530341807507. THE SHIPMENT WAS TENDERED FOR GROUND SERVICE BY BLACKMAN PLUMBING SUPPLY (A WHOLLY OWNED SUBSIDIARY OF FERGUSON) LOCATED AT 1595 LAKELAND AVENUE, BOHEMIA, NY 11716. THE COSIGNEE WAS LISTED AS BLACKMAN PLUMBING SUPPLY 348 BROADWAY, LYNBROOK, NY 11563. THE SHIPMENT SUBSEQUENTLY LEAKED INSIDE THE PACKAGE DURING TRANSPORTATION AND A BLACKMAN ASSOCIATE WAS EXPOSED DURING RECEIVING REQUIRING MEDICAL TREATMENT. AFTER INVESTIGATION BY FERGUSON IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE SHIPMENT CONTAINED QUART SIZE POLYETHYLENE CONTAINERS OF OATEY-HERCULES GLUG DRAIN OPENER IDENTIFIED AS UN3266, CORROSIVE LIQUID BASIC, INORGANIC, N.O.S., (SODIUM HYDROXIDE, POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE), 8, PGII, LIMITED QUANTITY.  WHEN TH RECEIVING ASSOCIATE OPENED UP THE BOX HE WAS UNAWARE A BOTTLE HAD SPILLED AND THE BOX CONTAINED CORROSIVE VAPORS. THE ASSOCIATE WAS ALSO UNAWARE THE BOX CONTAINED A LIMITED QUANTITY HAZARDOUS MATERIAL BECAUSE THE BOX WAS NOT MARKED. THE ASSOCIATE BREATHED IN CORROSIVE VAPORS FROM THE SPILLED LIQUID AND COMPLAINED OF RESPIRATORY DISTRESS AND MANAGEMENT IMMEDIATELY RESPONDED AND TOOK HIM TO THE EMERGENCY ROOM FOR TREATMENT AND OBSERVATION. THE RELEASED CORROSIVE LIQUID WAS CLEANED UP WITH A SPILL KIT AND DISPOSED OF BY OUR HAZARDOUS WASTE VENDOR, CLEAN HARBORS.
column169: AFTER RECEIVING NOTIFICATION OF THIS INCIDENT BY THE RECEIVING ASSOCIATE AT BLACKMAN, FERGUSON INVESTIGATED THE CIRCUMSTANCES SURROUNDING THIS SHIPMENT. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THAT ASSOCIATE WHO PACKAGED THE ORDER FAILED TO RECOGNIZE THAT THE PRODUCT REQUIRED SPECIFIC PACKAGING AS WELL AS SPECIFIC LABELING, AND HANDLING MARKINGS. THE ASSOCIATE HAS BEEN DISCIPLINED AND SUSPENDED FROM PACKAGING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS FOR SHIPMENT UNTIL FURTHER NOTICE AND WILL BE REQUIRED TO UNDERGO EXTENSIVE RE-TRAINING PRIOR TO BEING ALLOWED TO PACKAGE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS FOR SHIPMENT. FERGUSON HAS MODIFIED THE INTERNAL SYSTEM MESSAGE THAT IDENTIFIES HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ON THESE SHIPMENTS TO HELP ENSURE THAT ASSOCIATES RECOGNIZE THESE ITEMS ARE SUBJECT TO SPECIFIC PACKAGING REQUIREMENTS. ADDITIONALLY, INTERNAL DIRECTIVES ON SHIPPING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS IN LESS THAN THE MANUFACTURER'S CASE QUANTITY HAVE BEEN ISSUED COMPANY WIDE.

column168: On September 30, 2019, at 0702 ET, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics Terminal XAN regarding a cargo release. column168: On the morning of 9/9/19, Veolia employees discovered that a tote of caustic solution containing sodium hydroxide was leaking. Upon investigation , the employees were unable determine the  source of the small drips leaking from the tote so they decided to transfer the contents of the  leaking tote into another tote.  After transferring the contents of the leaking tote, the Veolia  employees investigated further to determine the source of the leak. Visible dents and scrapes of  the metal casing on the bottom of the tote caused from being loaded with the forklift were  identified.  It appears that the dented/damaged metal may have cracked the bottom outlet of the  tote at the middle of the bottom of the tote (though it could not be observed even when empty  without completely dismantling the tote). Veolia employees cleaned up the less than 2 gallons of  caustic solution that had leaked in the back of the original transport vehicle as well as the small  amount of solution at the Veolia Schenectady, NY 10 day in-transit facility.  The material that was  transferred into the new tote was sent to Stablex in Canada for appropriate disposal without any  further issues. All spill clean up materials were collected and sent for appropriate waste disposal.
column169: Veolia's best guess as to what happened was that the tote was damaged by the original offeror of  the shipment.  Veolia notified the customer that better care should be used when handling totes and try to avoid damaging the totes when using a forklift.

09/16/2019, at 12:36 hours, an FRA inspector in the CSXT Greenwich yard discovered the SHPX222842, a residue tank car of UN 1993 Waste Flammable Liquid, having a vapor release from the manway area of the rail car. The rail car was isolated and GEOCYCLE was notified along with Kemtell (no report # issued).   HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the tank car was having a vapor release from the manway area of the rail car. Upon checking the manway gasket. The gasket was found to be improperly installed and cracked. The issue identified where corrected and were communicated to the shipper Garfield Robrsten 803-496-1471, Garfield.Robrsten@Geocycle.com . Contractor personnel installed new nozzle gasket secured the rail car. The rail car was released to transportation. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1.   Cause Code: NARRI:

column42: AEROSOLS, FLAMMABLE, (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column168: During a routine secondary audit, I randomly chose this shipment to inspect more closely. The outer box was marked as an Overpack. The DG declaration also indicated the shipment was overpacked. There are 13 boxes in the shipment, 11 white boxes and 2 brown boxes. The 11 white boxes each contained 12 aerosol-type cans(168g) and each brown box contained 6 aerosol-type(255g) cans. As the shipment was offered as an overpack I expected that the inner cans would be in another properly marked& labeled box. When I flipped the outer box over I saw cans between where the bottom flaps failed to meet in the middle of the box. There was no inner box, just aerosol cans- thus not an overpack, rather just a combination package. I had the freight held pending an FAA inspection.

column168: Driver was preparing to hook the hose to the trailer's external valve. A black residue came out from the bleeder valve and was captured in a bucket, however, no product drained out. To stop the leak she tried to tighten the external valve more, however it was as tight as she could get it.  .  A facility employee came to assist and was able to stop the leak by cranking on the external valve even more.    No product was leaking at this point and the dust cap was off so the driver was able to hook up and completed the offload.   The spilled product was immediately cleaned up by the facility employees and there is no further assistance required.

column168: Envirite of Pennsylvania, Inc. driver was returning to the treatment facility located at 730 Vogelsong Road, York PA.  His cargo tank was loaded with stripping process wastewater.  The driver contacted the carrier's emergency coordinator at 11:21 AM.  He reported that he was on Interstate 81 on the Route 15 south bridge and the tank manhole hatch assembly had came off the unit while in transit from the generator site.  The entire manhole hatch assembly ejected from the tanker and landed on the roadway.  The driver was able to stop the truck and pull off the roadway without any of the waste releasing to the ground.  There were no injuries or accidents when the manhole hatch assembly came free.  Local emergency services and spill response were contacted by the emergency coordinator.  Upon review of the scene it was confirmed there was no spillage of waste.  As the tanker manhole hatch assembly was no longer intact, the contents of the tanker were transferred to another cargo tank for safe transport to the treatment facility.
column169: The manufacturer of the cargo tank manhole hatch assembly was contacted regarding the incident.  They stated that the technology the manufacturer uses when manufacturing the manhole hatch assembly was changed and there is a new model available. Taking this under consideration, Envirite of Pennsylvania, Inc. has decided to replace all the manhole hatch assemblies on this tank with new hatches.

column62: Inadequate Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Preparation for Transportation
column168: ON 9/5/2019 AT 13:33 HOURS, THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY'S (KCS) CRITICAL INCIDENT DESK WAS NOTIFIED OF THE PRESENCE OF THE SMELL OF LPG GAS AT THE SOUTH END OF THE KCS KNOCHE YARD IN KANSAS CITY, MO. THE ODOR WAS BELIEVED TO BE COMING FROM A LOADED ETHYL MERCAPTAN TANK CAR, UTLX 900597. THE KCS ENVIRONMENTAL & HAZMAT DEPARTMENT MOBILIZED INTERNAL RESPONDERS, AND A RAILROAD QUALIFIED RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INVESTIGATE.   UPON ARRIVAL, TWO LIQUID VALVES AND THE VAPOR VALVE, THE VAPOR LINE PLUG, AND THE TWO LIQUID LINE PLUGS WERE ALL FOUND TO BE LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT. ALL VALVES AND PLUGS WERE SECURED. AIR MONITORING CONTINUED FOR THE NEXT HOUR TO ENSURE THE LEAK HAD BEEN MITIGATED. A RESIDUAL ODOR WAS STILL DETECTED AFTER THE VALVES AND PLUGS WERE TIGHTENED. EACH PLUG WAS REMOVED INDIVIDUALLY AND NEW TEFLON TAPE APPLIED BEFORE REINSTALLING THEM TOOL TIGHT. A BLEACH SOLUTION WAS THEN APPLIED TO MITIGATE THE ODOR. THE PRESSURE PLATE WAS SNOOPED, AND DID NOT REVEAL A LEAK. ONCE THE ODOR DISSIPATED AND THE CAR WAS VERIFIED SECURE, UTLX 900597 WAS PLACED BACK INTO TRANSPORTATION.  FILE NOTE: ITEM 19-THE QUANTITY RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED BASED ON THE BEST INFORMATION AVAILABLE AT THE TIME OF FILING. THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED AS A 'BULK' SHIPMENT, AKA ONE CAR LOAD, THEREFORE THE EXACT AMOUNT OFFERED IN THIS PACKAGE IS NOT KNOWN TO THE CARRIER. THIS CARRIER DOES NOT HAVE ACCESS TO MASS BALANCE DATA WHICH CAN EXACTLY QUANTIFY THIS VALUE.
column169: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) NOTIFIED SHIPPER OF THIS RELEASE. NON ACCIDENTAL RELEASES (NAR) CAN BE DEVASTATING ON SEVERAL DIFFERENT LEVELS. THEY CAN CAUSE PERSONAL INJURY, ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE, DISRUPT RAIL YARDS, ADJACENT FACILITIES AND COMMUNITIES, AND SNARL TRAIN OPERATIONS FOR HUNDREDS OF MILES AND BOTH DIRECTIONS. NARS ARE TROUBLESOME TO ALL BECAUSE THEY ARE, BY AND LARGE, PREVENTABLE. FOR NON ACCIDENT RELEASES (A.K.A. PACKAGE CLOSURE ISSUES SUCH AS THIS), THE SHIPPER IS REQUESTED TO CONDUCT A ROOT-CAUSE INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE(S) OF RELEASE AND TO THEN FACILITATE CORRECTIVE ACTION TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. IT IS REQUESTED THAT THE SHIPPER SHARE THEIR FINDINGS WITH KCS. (PLEASE DIRECT YOUR ROOT CAUSE INVESTIGATION RESULTS AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO STEVE MCNEALY, KCS RAILWAY, P.O. BOX 2019335, KANSAS CITY, MO 64121. THE SHIPPER CAN REFERENCE HTTP://NAR.AAR.COM FOR HELP UNDERSTANDING AND PREVENTING NARS.

column168: During routine inspection, facility personnel identified a release from a transport trailer. An internal emergency response team was dispatched. In appropriate personal protective equipment, verified by the internal health & safety professionals, the response team successfully over-packed the compromised container into an authorized container for transportation. column62: Human Error; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: AN EAST PENN DRIVER WAS MAKING DELIVERIES AND PICKING UP JUNK LEAD ACID BATTERIES AT HIS DELIVERY STOPS. HE REACHED HIS NEXT DESTINATION, THE MONROE STORE PARKING LOT IN PITTSBURGH. WHEN HE GOT OUT OF HIS TRUCK HE NOTICED SMOKE COMING FROM THE BACK OF HIS TRUCK. HE OPENED THAT BACK OF THE TRUCK AND REALIZED A PALLET OF BATTERIES WERE ON FIRE. THE DRIVER AND A COUPLE OF EMPLOYEES AT THE STORE TRIED TO PUT OUT THE FIRE WITH A FIRE EXTINGUISHER BUT THE BURNING PALLET OF BATTERIES WAS AT THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. THERE WAS TOO MUCH BLACK SMOKE THEY COULD NOT SEE TO GET TO THE BURNING PALLET. THEY CALLED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND WAITED AND WATCHED THE BURNING TRAILER UNTIL THE FIRE COMPANY ARRIVED.  ERTS WAS CONTACTED TO DISPATCH AN ENVIRONMENTAL CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR TO HELP WITH THE CLEAN UP. BY THE TIME THE CONTRACTOR ARRIVED AT THE SCENE THE FIRE WAS OUT. THE CONTRACTOR COLLECTED THE LITTLE BIT OF LIQUID THAT WAS COMING FROM THE TRAILER. NO STORM DRAINS OR GROUND WAS IMPACTED. INSIDE THE TRAILER WERE MELTED PALLETS OF BATTERIES. A TOW SERVICE WAS CALLED TO HAVE THE BURNT TRAILER TOWED BACK TO THE PITTSBURGH WAREHOUSE WHERE THERE WAS MORE ROOM TO WORK ON THE TRAILER TO REMOVE THE PRODUCT. EAST PENN EMPLOYEES CLEANED OUT THE DEBRIS FROM THE TRAILER SO THEY COULD GET AT THE BURNT PALLETS OF BATTERIES. FOUR PALLETS WERE RE-WRAPPED AND SENT BACK TO EAST PENN MANUFACTURING CO.'S LYONS STATION FACILITY WHERE THE BATTERIES WENT TO OUR SECONDARY LEAD SMELTER FOR RECLAIM AND RECYCLE. THE CLEAN UP DEBRIS WAS BAGGED AND WILL BE PUT INTO DISPOSAL DRUMS TO BE PICKED UP BY CLEAN HARBORS FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  NOT SURE OF THE CAUSE OF THE FIRE. IT IS POSSIBLE THAT IT WAS AN INTERNAL PALLET FIRE. ONE -- TWO PALLETS FROM A CUSTOMER WERE ALREADY WRAPPED BY THE CUSTOMER WHEN RECEIVED. IT IS POSSIBLE THAT TERMINALS WERE TOUCHING EACH OTHER INTERNALLY ON THE PALLET.
column169: EAST PENN MANUFACTURING CO.'S DISTRICT MANAGER WENT TO THE LAST CUSTOMER THAT WE PICKED UP THE PALLETS OF BATTERIES THAT WE BELIEVE STARTED THE FIRE. DISCUSSIONS ON PROPER STACKING AND WRAPPING PROCEDURES WERE DISCUSSED. THE CUSTOMER ALSO CAME OUT TO OUR EAST PENN PITTSBURGH FACILITY TO VIEW OUR OPERATIONS AS WE WENT OVER THE PROPER STACKING AND WRAPPING PROCEDURES. EAST PENN ALSO WENT OVER PROPER STACKING AND WRAPPING PROCEDURES WITH OUR OWN EMPLOYEES AND DRIVERS.

The 55 gallon drum was being off loaded from a truck at the Veolia 10 day in-transit facility when the drum was tipped in order to move it and liquid material came out around the bung.  This type of drum  contains an inner bladder liner.  It is believed that there was either a leak in the liner or the drum was overfilled resulting in liquid between the bladder liner and the wall of the drum.  There were no signs of damage or leaks when the container was offered for transportation and initially loaded onto the  vehicle.  The leaking 55 gallon drum was overpacked into another container to prevent any further leaks.
column169: To prevent this incident from reoccurring Veolia will perform an in-house training to educate the field technicians on these types of the drums and the potential hazards associated with them being over filled.

column168: TCIX 7378 was found during random tank car inspections to be releasing vapor from the manway.  Inspection of the car found the manway secure with all swing bolts in position and tool-tight.    Inspection of the manway gasket found what appeared to be deformation, i.e. ?crinkling? of the gasket on the inner circumference of the gasket.  There was also a tear or separation of the gasket on the outboard circumference of the gasket but that damage did not appear to have contributed to the release of vapor.    One Federal Railroad Administration hazardous materials inspector was exposed to the vapor released from the car and was transported to the hospital for examination where he was treated and released.
column169: Ensure gaskets are inspected and maintained to provide adequate sealing properties while the car is in transportation.

column169: THE COMPANY HAS A ROLLOVER PREVENTION POLICY TITLED, "SLIP OFF STAY OFF" WITH CAB POSTERS AND TRAINING REMINDERS. THE IDEA IS TO BRING THE VEHICLE UNDER CONTROL WITHOUT ATTEMPTING TO RADICALLY CHANGE THE PATH WHICH CAN CAUSE LIQUID LOAD SHIFTING AND ADD TO THE POTENTIAL FOR OVERTURN. AFTER EACH SUCH ACCIDENT A COMMITTEE REVIEWS THE INVESTIGATIVE FACTS TO DETERMINE  WHETHER THE DRIVER FOLLOWED COMPANY SAFETY PRACTICES AND WHETHER DISCIPLINARY ACTIONS ARE APPROPRIATE.

column168: On September 30, 2019, at 2306 ET, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics Terminal XCN regarding a cargo release. It was reported that due to improper loading, (1) 330-gallon plastic tote of Entegrate SC 2015 (Flammable liquid, n.o.s., UN1993) was damaged, releasing approximately 1 quart of product on to the trailer floor.  A contractor was dispatched to clean up the release using absorbents and the proper PPE.  The remaining product in the damaged tote was transferred into a new tote and forwarded on to the consignee.  The cut up damaged tote, spent absorbents and all other debris were containerized in (1) 55-gallon metal drum which was then staged onsite at OS&D for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: ON 9/10/2019 AT 1215 HOURS, A KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCS) TRAIN DERAILED 8 CARS IN THE KCS LAREDO, TX RAIL YARD. OF THE 8 CARS, ONLY UTLX 209475 (LOADED CLASS 3, ULTRA LOW SULFUR DIESEL) WAS REPORTED LEAKING. THE KCS ENVIRONMENTAL &  HAZMAT DEPARTMENT MOBILIZED A RAILROAD QUALIFIED RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO CONDUCT DAMAGE ASSESSMENT AND SECURE THE LEAKING TANK CAR.  UPON ARRIVAL, THE RESPONSE CONTRACTOR FOUND UTLX 209475 ON ITS SIDE, LEAKING FROM THE TOP MANWAY. THE SHIPPER HAD FAILED TO PROPERLY SECURE THE MANWAY BEFORE OFFERING THE CAR INTO TRANSPORTATION. THE RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS ABLE TO SLOW THE LEAK TO A DRIP BY TIGHTENING ALL MANWAY SECUREMENT BOLTS. CONTAINMENT WAS DEPLOYED UNDER THE NOW-SLOWED RELEASE. SHORTLY THEREAFTER, THE RESPONSE CONTRACTOR COMPLETELY STOPPED THE DIESEL RELEASE BY FURTHER TIGHTENING THE MANWAY SECUREMENT BOLTS. IT IS ESTIMATED THAT A TOTAL OF 50 GALLONS OF DIESEL WAS RELEASED FROM UTLX 209475. REMEDIAL ACTIONS WERE TAKEN ON THE SPILL AREA, AND ALL RAIL CARS WERE SAFETY RE-RAILED. LADING TRANSFERS ARE BEING SCHEDULED AND DAMAGED, PURGED AND CLEANED, RAIL CARS WILL BE SENT ON FLAT CARS UNDER OTMA'S TO HOME SHOP FOR REPAIRS.  FILE NOTE: ITEM 19-THE QUANTITY RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED BASED ON THE BEST INFORMATION AVAILABLE AT THE TIME OF FILING. THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED AS A 'BULK' SHIPMENT, AKA ONE CAR LOAD, THEREFORE THE EXACT AMOUNT OFFERED IN THIS PACKAGE IS NOT KNOWN TO THE CARRIER. THIS CARRIER DOES NOT HAVE ACCESS TO MASS BALANCE DATA WHICH CAN EXACTLY QUANTIFY THIS VALUE.
column169: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) NOTIFIED SHIPPER OF THIS RELEASE. NON ACCIDENTAL RELEASES (NAR) CAN BE DEVASTATING ON SEVERAL DIFFERENT LEVELS. THEY CAN CAUSE PERSONAL INJURY, ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE, DISRUPT RAIL YARDS, ADJACENT FACILITIES AND COMMUNITIES, AND SNARL TRAIN OPERATIONS FOR HUNDREDS OF MILES AND BOTH DIRECTIONS. NARS ARE TROUBLESOME TO ALL BECAUSE THEY ARE, BY AND LARGE, PREVENTABLE. FOR NON ACCIDENT RELEASES (A.K.A. PACKAGE CLOSURE ISSUES SUCH AS THIS), THE SHIPPER IS REQUESTED TO CONDUCT A ROOT-CAUSE INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE(S) OF RELEASE AND TO THEN FACILITATE CORRECTIVE ACTION TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. IT IS REQUESTED THAT THE SHIPPER SHARE THEIR FINDINGS WITH KCS. (PLEASE DIRECT YOUR ROOT CAUSE INVESTIGATION RESULTS AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO STEVE MCNEALY, KCS RAILWAY, P.O. BOX 219335, KANSAS CITY, MO 64121. THE SHIPPER CAN REFERENCE HTTP://NAR.AAR.COM FOR HELP UNDERSTANDING AND PREVENTING NARS.

At the beginning of the offload the driver partially opened the valves on his trailer and then walked the lines to check for leaks.  Everything looked good.  He continued to open his valves all the way and product started leaking from where his hose was connected to the trailer.  He shut down right away and then bled the pressure off his hoses to stop the leak.  Upon inspection he found that the gasket was a little worn on the edges but not cracked at all.  After replacing he was able to finish the offload with no further leaks.

column168: On September 13, 2019 at 1340 ET, Covenant Transport Group truck 118961. trailer 45087   experienced a five (5) - gallon release of UN1263, Paint (flammable), 3, PGIII "Sherwin Williams 404 White Acrylic Paint" from one (1) 5 - gallon poly pail due to improper loading. Covenant Transport Group obtained Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) to manage and oversee the incident. ERTS dispatched Lone Star Hazmat Response for emergency response and remediation activities. The contractor arrived onsite and confirmed approximately two cups of the five gallons had released to the asphalt below the trailer and the remaining product had released to a 35' x 12' area of the trailer however the paint was already dry. The contractor power washed the impacted areas but the paint would not come off. The damaged 5 - gallon poly pail was taken off site by the contractor for disposal.

DRIVER, OPERATING TRACTOR TOWING FULL CNG TRAILER, MANEUVERED TO AVOID STRIKING A DEER AT WHICH POINT HE STRUCK THE CONCRETE JERSEY BARRIER AND CAUSED THE TRAILER TO OVERTURN ONTO THE PASSENGER SIDE TRAVELING APPROXIMATELY 60 MPH. THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER THEN SLID ALONG THE SIDE OF THE ROAD AND JERSEY BARRIERS COMING TO REST IN THE BREAKDOWN LANE LAYING UP AGAINST THE BARRIER. DURING THE COURSE OF THE ACCIDENT THE TANK DRAIN VALVE ON THE UPPER PASSENGER SIDE TANK WAS SHEARED OFF CAUSING COMPRESSED NATURAL GAS TO BEGIN VENTING TO ATMOSPHERE. ONCE THE SCENE HAD BEEN SECURED BY EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL XNG PERSONNEL WERE ALLOWED ON SCENE TO ASSES DAMAGE. THE DECISION WAS MADE TO TRANSFER THE NATURAL GAS REMAINING THE TANK CYLINDERS TO EMPTY CNG TRAILERS OWNED BY XNG. XNG PROCEEDED TO RECOVER 291 MCF OF THE INITIAL 314 MCF THAT HAD BEEN LOADED TO THE TRAILER INVOLVED IN THE ACCIDENT. ONCE ALL AVAILABLE GAS HAD BEEN TRANSFERRED THE REMAINING GAS WAS VENTED TO ATMOSPHERE TO ENSURE MINIMAL RISK DURING THE RIGHTING AND RECOVERY PROCESS OF THE OVERTURNED TRAILER. A TOTAL OF 23 MCF WAS LOST DUE TO TANK DAMAGE AND VENTING DURING RECOVERY.

column168: 9:45AM - HAZCHEM RECEIVED A CALL FROM SPILL CENTER REGARDING A RESPONSE NEEDED FOR AN INK SPILL FOR N & M TRANSFER IN SCHILLER PARK, IL. A CREW IS ASSEMBLED AND DISPATCHED TO THE SITE.  10:50AM - CREW ARRIVES ON-SITE AND FINDS 1-55GAL. DRUM OF PRODUCT THAT HAD BEEN PUNCTURED MIDWAY AND LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 25 GAL. ONTO THE TRLR. FLOOR. CREW BEGINS CLEAN-UP; FREIGHT FROM THE REAR OF THE TRLR. IS UNLOADED USING HAZCHEM'S FORKLIFT, AND SKIDS ARE WIPED DOWN USING ABSORBENT PADS AND THE SKIDS ARE PLACED ONTO PLOY SHEETING. CREW THEN OVERPACKS THE DAMAGED DRUM INTO 1-85GAL. OTS DRUM AS RECOVERED MATERIAL. CREW APPLIES OIL DRY TO THE SPILL AREA ON THE TRLR. FLOOR. THE OIL DRY WAS WORKED IN TO ABSORB THE INK AND SPENT OIL DRY/PADS AND DEBRIS WAS COLLECTED AND DRUMMED AS WASTE.   THE CREW WAS UNABLE TO ACCESS THE FRONT HALF OF THE TRLR. DUE TO IT BEING LOADED WITH 14' PALLETS. THE DRIVER STATED THAT HE CALLED THEIR SAFETY REP. AND IT WAS DECIDED TO BRING THE TRLR. BACK TO THEIR WAREHOUSE IN NEENAH, WI. TO BE CLEANED THERE. CREW THEN PUT DOWN ADDITIONAL OIL DRY AND PLACED PADS BETWEEN THE 14' PALLETS TO ABSORB AND DIKE ANY REMAINING PRODUCT. HAZCHEM ER MGR. JOHNNY TURKOVICH ATTEMPTED TO CONTACT TRACIE AT SPILL CENTER TO INFORM HER BUT SHE WAS NOT REACHABLE. SHE REPLIED VIA TEXT MSG. THAT SHE WAS IN A MEETING. JOHNNY THEN SENT HER PROJECT PHOTOS AND INFORMED HER THAT THE DRIVER WAS RETURNING THE TRLR. TO THEIR WAREHOUSE AND THE TRLR. WAS NOT ACTIVELY LEAKING. TRACIE APPROVED VIA TEXT MSG. CREW THEN PROCEED TO RELOAD THE FREIGHT ONTO THE TRLR. AND SECURE THE LOAD. THE DRIVER DEPARTED THE SITE AT 1:10PM.  1:20PM - A TOTAL OF 2-55GAL. OTS DRUMS OF WASTE GENERATED. CREW MARKED THE DRUMS ACCORDINGLY AND LOADED THEM FOR TRANSPORT OFF-SITE FOR DISPOSAL. SUPPLIES AND EQUIPMENT ARE LOADED AND CREW DEPARTS SITE.  2:00PM - CREW RETURNS TO SHOP TO OFF-LOAD AND RESTOCK EQUIPMENT. PROJECT COMPLETE.  - DRUMMED WASTE SHIPPED TO TRADEBE IN EAST CHICAGO, IN. ON 09/27/19 UNDER MANIFEST #001017420WAS.

column168: CSI WAS RECEIVING ETHYLENE GLYCOL MONOBUTYL ETHER (EB) FROM A SUPPLIER INTO AN OUTDOOR STORAGE TANK LOCATED IN A CONCRETE DIKE AT THE SOUTH SIDE OF THE PRODUCTION & WAREHOUSE AREA. DURING THE OFFLOADING OF ETHYLENE GLYCOL MONOBUTYL ETHER, THE RECEIVING BULK TANK LEAKED FROM THE TOP MANWAY COVER AND ALL MATERIAL WAS COLLECTED IN THE IMPERIOUS CONCRETE DIKE. IT WAS RAINING DURING THE TRANSFER. THE CSI EMPLOYEE RESPONSIBLE FOR THE TRANSFER IMMEDIATELY ASKED THE DRIVER OF THE CTMV TO STOP THE TRANSFER WHEN HE SPOTTED LIQUID COMING FROM THE TOP COVER. IT IS ESTIMATED THAT THE SPILL WAS STOPPED WITHIN 30 SECONDS OR LESS. THE CSI EMPLOYEE FOLLOWED THE PROTOCOL FOR A SPILL AND INFORMED MANAGEMENT. THE SITUATION WAS ASSESSED AND THE INVENTORY CONTROL FOR THE FOR BULK TANK REVIEWED. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE INVENTORY WAS OFF RESULTING IN AN OVERCHARGE TO THE BULK TANK. 3 TIMES MORE EB AS CALCULATED FROM THE INVENTORY REVIEW WAS TRANSFERRED INTO A MIX TANK FROM THE BULK TANK. 3 TIMES MORE EB AS CALCULATED FROM THE INVENTORY REVIEW WAS TRANSFERRED INTO A MIX TANK FROM THE BULK TANK BEFORE COMPETING THE TRANSFER FROM THE CTMV. ALL MATERIAL SPILLED FROM THE MANWAY WAS CONTAINED IN THE IMPERVIOUS DIKE AND RECOVERED. THE MATERIAL WAS TRANSFER TO TOTES, WEIGHED AND PLACED INSIDE THE BUILDING IN A CONTAINMENT AREA. THE RAINWATER AND SPILLED ED WAS ANALYZED AND COLLECTED UNTIL ANALYSIS SHOWED NO LEVEL OF THE EB IN THE DIKE AREA. THE ANALYSIS OF THE MATERIAL COLLECTED ALONG WITH TOTAL WEIGHT OF MATERIAL COLLECTED CONFIRMED THE SPILL AMOUNT TO BE APPROXIMATELY 88 LBS OR 11.5 GALLONS  (BASED ON DENSITY OF EB)
column169: THE SENSOR FOR BOTH LOW AND HIGH LEVELS ON BULK TANK WILL BE RE-CALIBRATED AND A PROJECT OPENED TO INSTALL HIGH LEVEL ALARM SENSORS ON THE B13 TANK USING A FLOAT SYSTEM. NO SPECIFIC RECOMMENDATIONS ARE SUGGESTED FOR HAZMAT TRANSPORTATION OUTSIDE OF CSI CONTROL AT THIS TIME, DUE TO THE ROOT CAUSE BEING DETERMINED AS A FAILED SENSOR CALIBRATION ON THE OUTSIDE STORAGE TANK ON CSI PROPERTY.

column168: Driver Kermit Pérez was heading North on PR 52 (Luis A. Ferré Highway) with in tank truck property of Camioneros Cooperativa de Transporte y Carga, with a 10,000 gallon of regular gasoline load, from PUMA Energy.  The driver was conducting at 55 MPH in a 65 MPH area.  By KM 74.6 of Santa Isabel jurisdiction, the driver allegedly spotted a vehicle from Del Valle Group, a company doing repair jobs on the road at the moment. As the driver stated, the vehicle was located in the Emergency lane.  As the driver stated, in an attempt not to hit the vehicle, he made a rapid movement to the left side of the road, causing the rolling over of the tank truck.  The truck slides in the pavement hitting the security fences by the side of the road.  Due to the impact, the cabin detaches from the tank and slides  at a considerable distance, hitting security fences and that the above mentioned company has located in the road. The driver was taken on air ambulance to the Medical Center, and was attended in the intensive care unit, but in stable condition. One of the Del Valle Group employees received minor injuries in the incident.  The truck the tank and the vehicle suffered major damages. There was environmental impact, and a spill of approximately 8,000 gallons of gasoline. This spill was managed by RICLEM, a specialized and certified company.
column169: To this moment, the specific cause or causes for the accident are not finally determined, this incident is under thorough investigation.  As a preventive measure, we are not allowing the driver involved in the accident back to work until the matter is finally investigated.  Our Drivers are continuously receiving training on the importance of Key No. 1: Looking Always to the front. We are also conducting training sessions and conferences about the need of resting and avoid road fatigue and about defensive driving.

column168: Driver routed himself on an unfamiliar route between customer locations on a split load. Driver utilized GPS to determine route without obtaining confirmation from others. Driver ignored multiple advisory and truck restriction warning signs in advance of rollover site. The event occurred on 09/19/2019 at about 0630. No package failure. No release. Local fire departments and highway patrol initially responded, followed by our company personnel and DEQ representatives in addition to towing & recovery specialists. The decision was made to install check dams in the affected creek and call-in and stage a vac truck on-site ready for containment in case a package failure occurred during recovery. Refer to the attached fire department report for further details of the effort and outcome.
column169: We have included this event in our Fall Driver Meetings for conversation with every driver along with the reiteration of our (long standing) company policy to NOT rely on GPS for trip routing. This point will be stressed even more clearly during the training process with new hires and revisited on safety reviews with all drivers.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING THE TRAILER, ONE CARTON WAS FOUND PUNCTURED AND LEAKING. THE RELEASE WAS PROPERLY MANAGED. THE DAMAGED FREIGHT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND HELD PENDING DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER.
column169: DO NOT PUSH OTHER FREIGHT INTO HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WHEN LOADING THE TRAILER.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: ON 1 OCTOBER 2019, UYM MANAGEMENT ACCOMPANIED BY THEIR ENVIRONMENTAL CONSULTANT – MR. BRAD HELLAND FROM “IRC” MET WITH MR. TOM MACKIE FROM DOE AND THE LAND OWNER, MR. RICHARD CAMP TO DISCUSS THE INCIDENT AND THE WAY FORWARD.  AS DECIDED IN THE MEETING, UYM STARTED COVERING THE ENTIRE RAIL BED AFFECTED BY THE SPILL WITH A PLASTIC TARO TO PREVENT INFILTRATION OF RAIN AND/OR SNOW MELT WATER. ONLY UNCOVERING WHERN RAIL CAR ACTIVITY IS NECESSARY.  UYM HAS SUBMITTED TO ECOLOGY FOR APPROVAL A DRAFT INTERIM ACTION WORK PLAN THAT WILL OUTLINE HOW TO DETERMINE THE NATURE AND EXTENT OF THE RELEASE AND WHAT REMEDIAL ALTERNATIVES ARE PROPOSED FOR THE RELEASE SITE. THIS DRAFT INTERIM ACTION WORK PLAN WAS SUBMITTED TO ECOLOGY FOR REVIEW ON OCTOBER 14, 2019 TO MR. TOM MACKIE. DUE TO THE QUANTITY OF ACID SPILLED AND THE POTENTIAL FOR THE ACID TO MOBILIZE HEAVY METALS KNOWN TO EXIST IN FACILITY SOILS, UYM WILL WORK WITH ECOLOGY TO IMPLEMENT THE INTERIM ACTION WORK PLAN AS SOON AS POSSIBLE.   ON TUESDAY 15 OCTOBER 2019, A CONTARCTOR HIRED ON BEHALF OF UYM TOOK 7 SOIL BORINGS FOR SAMPLES IN THE AREA AROUND THE SPILL SITE TO DETERMINE THE EXTENT OF THE ACID SPILL. THE SAMPLES WILL BE SENT TO A N OUTSIDE LAB FOR ANALYSIS OF PH AND HEAVY METALS TO DETERMINE THE DEPTH AND POTENTIAL OF MIGRATION DUE TO THE SPILL. MR. MACKIE FROM DOE WAS PRESENT DURING THE ACTIVITY.
column169: 1. ONE OF THE TWO METAL CAM ARMS OF THE CPVC COUPLING BROKE, EVIDENTLY DUE TO FATIGUE ALLOWING THE FLANGED CONNECTION TO SEPARATE CAUSING A MAJOR LEAK IN ACID. A. ACTION: ALL FITTINGS HAVE BE CHANGED TO STAINLESS STEEL “CAMLOK” FITTINGS AND WILL ROUTINELY REPLACED AS PER A SPECIFIED SCHEDULE.  2. THERE WAS NOT A VALVE ON THE LIQUID PIPE (“CHRISTMAS TREE”) WHICH MOUNTS ON THE TANK CAR AHEAD OF THE COUPLING, TO ALLOW SHUTTING OFF THE FLOW IF LIQUID. A. ACTION: A NEW 2” STAINLESS STEEL VALVE HAS BEEN ADDED TO THE “CHRISTMAS TREE” JUST ABOVE THE FLANGE THAT ATTACHES TO THE TANK CAR.  3. THERE WAS NO WAY TO DEPRESSURIZE THE CAR REMOTELY, SO THE ACID LEAK CONTINUED UNTIL THE PRESSURE INSIDE THE TANK CAR RETURNED TO ATOMOSPHERE PRESSURE. A. ACTION: THE ENTIRE COMPRESSED AIR CONTROL MANIFOLD HAS BEEN REPLACED WITH NEW CONTROLS AND A REMOTE EMERGENCY SHUTOFF VALVE AND PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE HAS BEEN ADDED AT GROUND LEVEL WHICH IS ACCESSIBLE AND EASILY ACTIVATED AT A SAFE DISTANCE FROM THE UNLOAD ARE.  4. OTHER IMPROVEMENTS A. THE STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURE (SOP) HAS BEEN REVIEWED, UPDATED, AND USED TO TRAIN ALL OPERATORS WHO ARE AUTHORIZED TO UNLOAD TANK CARS. B. AN EMERGENCY SHOWER HAS BEEN ADDED UP ON THE UNLOAD PLATFORM. C. GOGGLES HAVE BEEN ADDED TO THE REQUIRED PPE (VS. JUST SAFETY GLASSES UNDER THE FACE SHIELD) D. INSPECTION AND MANDATORY HOSE REPLACEMENT FREQUENCY HAS BEEN ADDED TO THE SOP. E. ADDITONAL FALL PROTECTION CHAIN HAS BEEN ADDED TO THE UNLOAD PLATFORM F. ALL UYM PERSONNEL HAVE GONE THROUGH RE-TRAINING ON THE SOP, DOT HAZ MAT HANDLING & SECURITY AWARENESS, AND ACID OPE

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: On September 10, 2019, at 0111 EST, XPO Logistics Notified ERTS of a spill that occurred on September 9, 2019, at 2200 EST. XPO reported that due to a roll over accident, and unknown amount of battery acid from an unknown amount of UN2794 batteries released to the trailer, asphalt roadway, and soil. The truck came to a rest in the highway ditch. The Fire Department on site stated the on ramp to I-25 South was shut down due to the accident. WY DOT hired Wayne Coleman Construction to complete all cleanup activities. The site was secured by the company. On September 9, 2019, at 1130 EST ERTS was contacted by the WY DOT who stated the ramp was re-opened on the night of September 10, 2019. On September 11, 2019, contractor completed all soil excavation.

column168: DRIVER OF OTHER VEHICLE WAS STOPPED AT THE INTERSECTION OF ROUTE 2. SHE SEEN THE TRACTOR TRAILER HEAD LIGHTS, BUT DID NOT BELIEVE THEY WERE VERY CLOSE. SHE PULLED OUT TO TURN LEFT AND REALIZED THE TRACTOR TRAILER WAS VERY CLOSE. SHE STOPPED IN HOPES TO AVOID A COLLISION BUT WAS NOT SUCCESSFUL. THE TRACTOR TRAILER STRUCK THE FRONT PORTION OF HER VEHICLE WITH THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER OF THE TRACTOR TRAILER STRUCK THE GUARD RAIL AND HIS TANK TURNED OVER AND PULLED THE TRACTOR ON IT TOP AND DOWN THE HILL. THE SUFFERED FACIAL INJURIES AND WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE HOSPITAL.
column169: THE COMPANY HAS A ROLLOVER PREVENTION POLICY TITLED, “SLIP OFF STAY OFF” WITH CAB POSTERS AND TRAINING REMINDERS. THE IDEA IS TO BRING THE VEHICLE UNDER CONTROL WITHOUT ATTEMPTING TO RADICALLY CHANGE THE PATH WHICH CAN CAUSE LIQUID LOAD SHIFTING AND ADD TO THE POTENTIAL FOR OVERTURN. AFTER EACH SUCH ACCIDENT A COMMITTEE REVIEWS THE INVESTIGATIVE FACTS TO DETERMINE WHETHER THE DRIVER FOLLOWED COMPANY SAFETY PRACTICES AND WHETHER DISCIPLINARY ACTIONS ARE APPROPRIATE.

column168: VSS TRACTOR/TANKER WAS HEADING WESTBOUND ON ALPINE RD TOWARDS THE TOWARDS THE TOWN OF LA HONDA CA. ALPINE RD IS A SLOW, TWISTY ROAD WITH SHARP HAIR PIN TURNS. ON THE LAST HAIR PIN TURN THE DRIVER WAS NOT ABLE TO COMPLETE THE ENTIRE TURN WITH THE TANKER TRAILER. THE PASSENGER SIDE OF THE TANKER TRAILER WHEELS STRUCK A TREE AT THE ROAD SIDE CAUSING THE REAR END OF THE TANKER TRAILER TO SLIDE INTO A RAVINE AND OVERTURN ONTO THE PASSENGER SIDE. AS THE TANKER OVERTURNED IT ALSO OVERTURNED THE TRACTOR. THE POSITION THE TANKER TRAILER LANDED IN DAMAGED THE DOME LID SEAL AS IT RESTED ON THE TREE TRUNK. A CALL TO 911 WAS PLACED AND FIRST RESPONDERS BEGAN ARRIVING  (SMCS, CHP, CAL FIRE, & LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENTS). VSS MANAGEMENT WAS NOTIFIED AND AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE.  VSS MANAGEMENT WAS NOTIFIED AND AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE. VSS MANAGEMENT NOTIFIED CAL-OES WHICH NOTIFIED DFG, US-EPA, STATE WATER, COUNTY HEALTH, NOAA, AND OTHER AGENCIES. VSS DISPATCHED 2X PUMP TRUCKS TO OFFLOAD THE REMAINING MATERIAL FROM THE OVERTURNED TANKER. FIRE PERSONNEL CUT 2X HOLES ON THE UPPER PORTION OF THE TANKER TO CREATE A DRAFT POINT. ONCE THE MATERIAL WAS OFFLOADED A TOW COMPANY WAS CONTRACTED TO REMOVE THE TANKER FROM THE RAVINE. THE TRACTOR AND TANKER WERE RIGHTED TOGETHER TO REMOVE THE TANKER FROM THE RAVINE. THE TRACTOR AND TANKER WERE RIGHTED TOGETHER THEN SEPARATED FOR THE TOW OFF SITE. APPROX 800-1000 GALLONS OF STYRAFLEX LEAKED INTO THE TRIBUTARY THAT FLOWED INTO ALPINE CREEK. A MASSIVE CLEAN UP EFFORT WAS UNDERTAKEN TO RESTORE THE CREEK AND WATER QUALITY.
column169: THROUGH THE COURSE OF THE INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE DRIVER WAS USING A NAVIGATIONAL AID THAT IS COMMONLY USED BY CLASS A DRIVERS THAT LED HIM DOWN THIS ROAD. ADDITIONALLY, THE ROAD ENTRANCE WAS NOT INDICATED THAT THIS ROAD WAS NOT SUITABLE FOR TRUCKS OF THIS LENGTH. LASTLY, OUR DISPATCHING DEPARTMENT WILL BE PROVIDING SPECIFIC ROUTES TO OUR DRIVERS TO PREVENT THIS KIND OF INCIDENT IN THE FUTURE.

column168: DRIVER WAS SLOWING DOWN PRIOR TO CROSSING A RAILROAD TRACK IN THE ENTRANCE OF CF INDUSTRIES PROPERTY, WHEN THE BAFFLE INSIDE THE CARGO TANK BROKE LOOSE CAUSING THE BAFFLE TO STRIKE THE INTERNAL PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE. THIS CAUSED THE RELIEF VALVE TO SHEER OFF, WHICH CAUSED THE VAPOR TO ESCAPE FROM THE TANK. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED AND ANOTHER TRAILER WAS BROUGHT TO THE SCENE AND THE PRODUCT FROM THE DAMAGED CARGO TANK WAS OFF LOADED ONTO NEW CARGO TANK TO DECREASE THE AMOUNT LOST AND DURATION OF THE LEAK.
column169: UPON INTERNAL INSPECTION OF THE TRAILER ON 10/31/19 THE TRAILER WAS FOUND TO HAVE A BROKEN BAFFLE THAT STRUCK THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE. THE RELIEF VALVE BODY BROKE ON THE STEM THAT HOLDS THE SEAL. THE SPRING AND BOTTOM HALF OF THE STEM WERE FOUND IN THE BOTTOM OF THE TRAILER, THE UPPER STEM WERE FOUND IN THE BOTTOM OF THE TRAILER, THE UPPER STEM AND SEAL WERE NOT RECOVERED AT THE LOCATION. THE MAIN BODY OF THE RELIEF VALUE WAS REMOVED, THE TRAILER WAS FULLY INSPECTED INCLUDING PRESSURE TEST, NEW BAFFLES INSTALLED, BLACK LIGHT INSPECTION, NEW RELIEF VALVES, LEAK TESTED AND VISUALLY INSPECTED. THE TRAILER HAS BEEN RETURNED TO IN-SERVICE STATUS.

column42: PRINTING INK, FLAMMABLE OR PRINTING INK RELATED MATERIAL (INCLUDING PRINTING INK THINNING OR REDUCING COMPOUND), FLAMMABLE
column168: On September 23, 2019, at approximately 10:00 PM CDT, a drum containing printer ink belonging to Landstar System Holdings, Inc.(LSHI) was punctured during offload at the above-referenced location. As a result, approximately thirty(30) gallons of printer ink were released to the unit's floor and undercarriage, as well as the asphalt and gravel surface underneath. LSHI retained Cura Emergency Services, LC(CES) to manage the cleanup. CES dispatched Lewis Environmental Group(LEG) to initiate corrective actions. Following a site assessment, LEG personnel observed approximately thirty(30) gallons of printer ink released to the unit's bed and undercarriage, as well as the asphalt and gravel surfaces beneath. LEG utilized simple green, isopropyl alcohol, calcium, Iime and rust remover, wire brushes, and absorbent pads to remediate the impacted unit floor and undercarriage. All impacted brushes and absorbents were collected and containerized into one(1) 55-gallon drum for transport and disposal. Site staff utilized granular absorbents to remediate the impacted asphalt and gravel surfaces. Site staff took ownership of all spent absorbents. LEG secured the site and demobilized, noting no further actions required.
